# Complexity metrics and feature boundaries (Rust / Rhino)

## There is no AbcSize in the Rust compiler

**RuboCop’s `Metrics/AbcSize`** (assignments + branches + conditions) is **Ruby-only**. The Rust compiler does not ship an identical metric, and there is no standard “ABC size” for Rust source.

**Practical substitute:** [Clippy](https://github.com/rust-lang/rust-clippy) is the default static analysis for Rust. The closest built-in, widely used signal is **`cognitive_complexity`**, with thresholds in **`clippy.toml`** in this repository. It is a different formula than AbcSize but pursues the same goal: **stop functions from turning into an unreadable tangle of branches and nesting**. Other useful pressure points include **arity** and **nesting** lints, enabled deliberately so they do not fight normal GUI or FFI code.

## What to run in automation

- **`cargo clippy` is not part of `cargo build`.** A normal compile does not run these checks. Keep quality visible by:
  - Running **`cargo clippy`** (or the **`cargo qcheck` alias** from **`.cargo/config.toml`**) before you merge, and
  - Wiring the same command into **CI** (recommended) on every push or pull request to `main` / your default branch.
- Treat a failing or warning-burdened Clippy run the same class of problem as a failing test: **fix by refactoring**; do not silence Clippy with `allow` (see `clippy-no-suppress.mdc`).

## Six-file scatter rule (one behavior → consolidate)

**Purpose:** One user-visible behavior should have **one obvious home** in code. If implementing it already touches many production files, the design is probably wrong — **consolidate in the same workstream**, do not ship a web of one-off hooks.

### When it applies

You are delivering **one** behavior change: a single feature scenario, one bug-fix path, or one acceptance story in `docs/features/`. Count production files you **had to edit** for that behavior only.

| Count toward the limit | Do **not** count |
|---|---|
| `src/**/*.rs`, `build.rs` | Docs-only edits (`docs/`, README notes) |
| Behavior-changing scripts under `data/` | Release / packaging assets |
| Tests added **only** for this behavior | Unrelated drive-by fixes in other features |

**Threshold:** more than **six** production files → **stop and consolidate before the task is done.** This is mandatory, not a suggestion for a later refactor.

### How to consolidate

1. **Stop scattering** — do not add another call site in a seventh file.
2. **Pick an owner** — one module or small directory that owns the behavior end-to-end.
3. **Expose a narrow API** — a few functions or one small type; hide details inside the owner.
4. **Rewire dependents** — other files call only that API; delete duplicate branches and stale fallbacks the move exposes.
5. **Ship together** — behavior and consolidation land in the same delivery. Split a PR only when review size forces it, not as an open-ended follow-up.

### Layer boundaries (keep these thin)

UI, playback engine, persistence, and platform stay separate. Feature-specific control flow and types live **in the owner**; outer layers remain adapters. The goal is not “fewer files everywhere,” but **no lockstep edits across six unrelated modules** for the next small tweak.

### Agent shorthand

**One behavior, one home.** Past six production files → pause, consolidate, rewire through a small API, then finish — **do not ship the scattered version.**

## Module length (soft target ~300 lines)

**Goal:** keep source files small enough to review, navigate, and edit safely (including with AI). The project **recommends** keeping Rust files under `src/` around **300 lines** or less when it is practical.

- **`clippy::too_many_lines`** (see **`clippy.toml`**, **`too-many-lines-threshold = 300`**) is set to **warn** (not **deny**). It applies per function but is the only line-count signal in the build.
- **`.cursor/rules/refactor-touched-longest.mdc`** is the matching policy at the module level: every request that edits an oversized module (> 300 lines) must shrink it in the same turn. There is no hard cap in tooling; the rule is the only enforcement.
- If **several** modules are over the limit, prefer **one file per refactor**, working from the **longest** file downward (largest payoffs first, smaller diffs). Do not try to “fix every oversized file” in a single pass unless the work is already scoped that way.
- When you **do** split a file: remove dead code and duplication first; then extract cohesive, feature-shaped modules with narrow boundaries (UI / mpv / storage), without growing the codebase just to hit a number.
- **`include!` splits** (and any extra modules created for length) must use **meaningful filenames** that reflect responsibility (e.g. `chrome_fullscreen_and_fit.rs`), not ordinal names like `1.rs` / `part2.rs`, so separation of concerns stays obvious in the tree and in reviews.

## Where configuration lives

- **`clippy.toml`** — thresholds for `cognitive_complexity`, `too_many_lines`, and other Clippy config.
- **`Cargo.toml` → `[lints]`** — project-wide lint level for selected Clippy lints.
- **`.cursorrules`**, **`.cursor/rules/refactor-touched-longest.mdc`**, and this rule — human and agent policy; not a replacement for `cargo clippy` on the machine.
